Description.note: Tara Glynn Colburn (né́e Tarasenka Pankiv) was born in 1925 in Zagreb, Croatia into an artistic family. After living in Germany, then Paris into her early adult years, she moved to Los Angeles, Calif. She became a photographer later in her life and even staged at least 6 exhibitions of her photographs in Europe and India. Colburn was also a staunch patron of opera and was a founding board member of the Los Angeles Opera Company from its beginnings in 1986. After Colburn died in 2003, her son, Cyril Wohrer, known as Chandrasekhar Acarya Das, took his mother's ashes to India where he put them, in their urn, into the Ganges River near Myapur, world headquarters of the International Society for Krishna Consciousness.
Title: Tara Colburn photographs of India, Iran, and Nepal, circa 1993-2003
Description.abstract: Photographs recording the daily life and family relationships among tribal peoples of India in some of its least-known and most rarely photographed regions. The photos were taken in the 10-year course of Tara Colburn travels while searching for her son who had joined the International Society for Krishna Consciousness.
Relation.isPartOf: Tara Colburn Photographs of India, Iran, and Nepal (Collection 434). Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA

Description.note: Slide held by UCLA Library Department of Special Collections, Collection no. 434, box 19, folder 4.|~|Koyas are a Dravadian tribe, a sub group of the Gonds of the Bastar region in Chattisgarh. Their dialect is Koyi. They are a pastoral community. Headgear made out of Bison horns, to which are attached strings of cowrie which covers the face. This “Maheshusingh topi” headgear is worn during festivals such as Chait parab (or “hunting festival”) during the month of March/April, and Pus parab in November/December when they play a double barrel drum called a “dhol” wearing this headgear while the girls dance to its beat. Koya men playing the dhol drum. Woman wearing a crown made out of an alloy of copper and tin—they wear it only when they dance during festival times. This woman's face is tattooed from her forehead, around under her eyes and cheeks, and all the way down to her chin. A young unmarried woman following the tradition of tattooing her face.
Title: Headgear made out of Bison horns, Iralgundi, October 1998
